<h1>The Reinvestment Scorecard</h1>

### Purpose  
The scorecard asks: **“Are resource rents being converted into future-proof assets?”** It aggregates five metrics:  

| Metric | High | Moderate | Low |
|--------|------|----------|-----|
| **Sustainable CapEx share** (renewables, circular economy, etc.) | > 30 % | 10–30 % | < 10 % :contentReference[oaicite:4]{index=4} |
| **Reserve-Replacement Ratio** | > 120 % | 80–120 % | < 80 % :contentReference[oaicite:5]{index=5} |
| **Reinvestment Rate** (CapEx / OCF) | > 100 % | 50–100 % | < 50 % :contentReference[oaicite:6]{index=6} |
| **Carbon-transition progress** | Net-zero ≤ 2040, Scope-3 plan | Net-zero 2050 | No credible plan :contentReference[oaicite:7]{index=7} |
| **Social & human capital spend** | Rising, impact based | Stable | Falling |

### Case snapshot  
Freeport-McMoRan scored *Low* on diversification (< 5 % green CapEx), Anglo *High* on reserve replacement (Quellaveco copper), Ørsted *High* across the board after exiting fossil fuels :contentReference[oaicite:8]{index=8}.  

> Firms that rank *Low* are effectively “eating the seed corn” and would face a **larger user-cost deduction** in sustainable accounts :contentReference[oaicite:9]{index=9}.

